df-tsk
blocks.content: The class of all Tarski classes. Tarski classes is a phrase coined by Grzegorz Bancerek in his article _Tarski's Classes and Ranks_, Journal of Formalized Mathematics, Vol 1, No 3, May-August 1990. A Tarski class is a set whose existence is ensured by Tarski's axiom A (see ~ ax-groth and the equivalent axioms). Axiom A was first presented in Tarski's article _Über unerreichbare Kardinalzahlen_. Tarski introduced the axiom A to enable ZFC to manage inaccessible cardinals. Later Grothendieck introduced the concept of Grothendieck universes and showed they were equal to transitive Tarski classes. (Contributed by FL, 30-Dec-2010.)

thm eltskg(setvar s0, setvar s1, class c0, class c1) {

  -| diffss(s0, s1)

  elab2g(hs0, c0, c1, ctsk, wa(wral(s0, c0, wa(wss(cpw(cv(s0)), c0), wrex(s1, c0, wss(cpw(cv(s0)), cv(s1))))), wral(s0, cpw(c0), wo(wbr(cv(s0), cen, c0), wcel(cv(s0), c0)))), wa(wral(s0, cv(hs0), wa(wss(cpw(cv(s0)), cv(hs0)), wrex(s1, cv(hs0), wss(cpw(cv(s0)), cv(s1))))), wral(s0, cpw(cv(hs0)), wo(wbr(cv(s0), cen, cv(hs0)), wcel(cv(s0), cv(hs0))))))

  raleqbi1dv(s0, cv(hs0), c0, wa(wss(cpw(cv(s0)), cv(hs0)), wrex(s1, cv(hs0), wss(cpw(cv(s0)), cv(s1)))), wa(wss(cpw(cv(s0)), c0), wrex(s1, c0, wss(cpw(cv(s0)), cv(s1)))))
  anbi12d(wceq(cv(hs0), c0), wss(cpw(cv(s0)), cv(hs0)), wrex(s1, cv(hs0), wss(cpw(cv(s0)), cv(s1))), wss(cpw(cv(s0)), c0), wrex(s1, c0, wss(cpw(cv(s0)), cv(s1))))
  sseq2(cv(hs0), c0, cpw(cv(s0)))
  rexeq(s1, cv(hs0), c0, wss(cpw(cv(s0)), cv(s1)))
  raleqbidv(s0, cpw(cv(hs0)), cpw(c0), wceq(cv(hs0), c0), wo(wbr(cv(s0), cen, cv(hs0)), wcel(cv(s0), cv(hs0))), wo(wbr(cv(s0), cen, c0), wcel(cv(s0), c0)))
  pweq(cv(hs0), c0)
  orbi12d(wceq(cv(hs0), c0), wbr(cv(s0), cen, cv(hs0)), wcel(cv(s0), cv(hs0)), wbr(cv(s0), cen, c0), wcel(cv(s0), c0))
  breq2(cv(hs0), c0, cv(s0), cen)
  eleq2(cv(hs0), c0, cv(s0))
  df-tsk(hs0, s0, s1)
  diff.hs0.c(c0)
  diff.hs0.w(wa(wral(s0, c0, wa(wss(cpw(cv(s0)), c0), wrex(s1, c0, wss(cpw(cv(s0)), cv(s1))))), wral(s0, cpw(c0), wo(wbr(cv(s0), cen, c0), wcel(cv(s0), c0)))))
  diff.cv.s(s1, hs0)
  diffss.ex(s1, hs0)
  diff.wceq.s(s0, cv(hs0), c0)
  diff.cv.s(s0, hs0)
  diffss.ex(s0, hs0)
  diff.hs0.s(s1)
  diff.hs0.s(s0)

blocks.name: tskpwss
blocks.content: First axiom of a Tarski class. The subsets of an element of a Tarski class belong to the class. (Contributed by FL, 30-Dec-2010.) (Proof shortened by Mario Carneiro, 20-Sep-2014.)
blocks.origin:
thm tskpwss(class c0, class c1) {
  |- wi(wa(wcel(c0, ctsk), wcel(c1, c0)), wss(cpw(c1), c0))
} = {
  sylan(wcel(c0, ctsk), wcel(c1, c0), wss(cpw(c1), c0), wral(hs0, c0, wss(cpw(cv(hs0)), c0)))
  syl(wcel(c0, ctsk), wral(hs0, c0, wss(cpw(cv(hs0)), c0)), wral(hs0, c0, wa(wss(cpw(cv(hs0)), c0), wrex(hs1, c0, wss(cpw(cv(hs0)), cv(hs1))))))
  simpld(wcel(c0, ctsk), wral(hs0, c0, wa(wss(cpw(cv(hs0)), c0), wrex(hs1, c0, wss(cpw(cv(hs0)), cv(hs1))))), wral(hs0, cpw(c0), wo(wbr(cv(hs0), cen, c0), wcel(cv(hs0), c0))))
  ibi(wcel(c0, ctsk), wa(wral(hs0, c0, wa(wss(cpw(cv(hs0)), c0), wrex(hs1, c0, wss(cpw(cv(hs0)), cv(hs1))))), wral(hs0, cpw(c0), wo(wbr(cv(hs0), cen, c0), wcel(cv(hs0), c0)))))
  eltskg(hs0, hs1, c0, ctsk)
  ralimi(hs0, c0, wa(wss(cpw(cv(hs0)), c0), wrex(hs1, c0, wss(cpw(cv(hs0)), cv(hs1)))), wss(cpw(cv(hs0)), c0))
  simpl(wss(cpw(cv(hs0)), c0), wrex(hs1, c0, wss(cpw(cv(hs0)), cv(hs1))))
  rspccva(hs0, c0, c1, wss(cpw(cv(hs0)), c0), wss(cpw(c1), c0))
  sseq1d(cpw(cv(hs0)), c0, cpw(c1), wceq(cv(hs0), c1))
  pweq(cv(hs0), c1)
  diff.hs0.s(hs1)
  diff.hs0.c(c0)
  diff.hs1.c(c0)
  diff.hs0.c(c1)
  diff.hs0.w(wss(cpw(c1), c0))
}

blocks.name: tsksdom
blocks.content: An element of a Tarski class is strictly dominated by the class. JFM CLASSES2 th. 1. (Contributed by FL, 22-Feb-2011.) (Revised by Mario Carneiro, 18-Jun-2013.)

blocks.name: tskssel
blocks.content: A part of a Tarski class strictly dominated by the class is an element of the class. JFM CLASSES2 th. 2. (Contributed by FL, 22-Feb-2011.) (Proof shortened by Mario Carneiro, 20-Sep-2014.)

blocks.name: tskss
blocks.content: The subsets of an element of a Tarski class belong to the class. (Contributed by FL, 30-Dec-2010.) (Revised by Mario Carneiro, 18-Jun-2013.)

blocks.name: tskin
blocks.content: The intersection of two elements of a Tarski class belongs to the class. (Contributed by FL, 30-Dec-2010.) (Proof shortened by Mario Carneiro, 20-Sep-2014.)

blocks.name: tsksn
blocks.content: A singleton of an element of a Tarski class belongs to the class. JFM CLASSES2 th. 2 (partly). (Contributed by FL, 22-Feb-2011.) (Revised by Mario Carneiro, 18-Jun-2013.)

blocks.name: tsktrss
blocks.content: A transitive element of a Tarski class is a part of the class. JFM CLASSES2 th. 8. (Contributed by FL, 22-Feb-2011.) (Revised by Mario Carneiro, 20-Sep-2014.)

blocks.name: tsksuc
blocks.content: If an element of a Tarski class is an ordinal number, its successor is an element of the class. JFM CLASSES2 th. 6 (partly). (Contributed by FL, 22-Feb-2011.) (Proof shortened by Mario Carneiro, 20-Sep-2014.)

blocks.name: rankcf
blocks.content: Any set must be at least as large as the cofinality of its rank, because the ranks of the elements of ` A ` form a cofinal map into ` ( rank `` A ) ` . (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 27-May-2013.)

blocks.name: r1omtsk
blocks.content: The set of hereditarily finite sets is a Tarski class. (The Tarski-Grothendieck Axiom is not needed for this theorem.) (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 28-May-2013.)

blocks.name: tskord
blocks.content: A Tarski class contains all ordinals smaller than it. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 8-Jun-2013.)

blocks.name: r1tskina
blocks.content: There is a direct relationship between transitive Tarski classes and inaccessible cardinals: the Tarski classes that occur in the cumulative hierarchy are exactly at the strongly inaccessible cardinals. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 8-Jun-2013.)

blocks.name: tskint
blocks.content: The intersection of an element of a transitive Tarski class is an element of the class. (Contributed by FL, 17-Apr-2011.) (Revised by Mario Carneiro, 20-Sep-2014.)

blocks.name: tskun
blocks.content: The union of two elements of a transitive Tarski class is in the set. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 20-Sep-2014.)

blocks.name: tskxp
blocks.content: The Cartesian product of two elements of a transitive Tarski class is an element of the class. JFM CLASSES2 th. 67 (partly). (Contributed by FL, 15-Apr-2011.) (Proof shortened by Mario Carneiro, 20-Sep-2014.)

blocks.name: tskmap
blocks.content: Set exponentiation is an element of a transitive Tarski class. JFM CLASSES2 th. 67 (partly). (Contributed by FL, 15-Apr-2011.) (Proof shortened by Mario Carneiro, 20-Sep-2014.)

blocks.name: tskurn
blocks.content: A transitive Tarski class is closed under small unions. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 22-Jun-2013.)
